{{Infobox holiday |holiday_name = Blue Mass |type = [[Mass (liturgy)|Mass]] |image = File:Police Week Blue Mass 2013 (8739375062).jpg |imagesize = |caption = Blue mass at [[St. Patrick's Catholic Church (Washington, D.C.)]] |official_name = |nickname = |observedby = [[Catholic Church|Catholics]], Other [[Christian]]s |litcolor = |longtype = |significance = Honor veterans of the Public Safety field |begins = |ends = |date = Varies by community |scheduling = |duration = <!-- e.g. "1 day", "1 week" --> |frequency = <!-- e.g. "annual", "every 4 years", "once" --> <!-- Use next three if holiday is the same day of the same week every year --> |week_ordinal = <!-- "first", "second", "last", etc. --> |weekday = <!-- "Sunday", "Monday", "Friday", etc. --> |month = <!-- "January", "February", "December", etc. --> <!-- Use next three if the date changes in an unusual pattern each year --> |date2014 = <!-- only for days that change each year --> |date2015 = <!-- only for days that change each year --> |date2016 = <!-- only for days that change each year --> |date2017 = <!-- only for days that change each year --> |celebrations = |observances = |relatedto = |firsttime = 1934 }}
<!--{{Infobox religion | name = Blue Mass | caption_background = | image = File:Police Week Blue Mass 2013 (8739375062).jpg | imagewidth = | alt = Blue Mass | caption = Blue Mass in Washington, D.C. | type = Mass | main_classification = Roman-Catholic | orientation = | scripture = {{bibleverse||Psalm|91:11|45}} | other_names = | publications = | website = | footnotes = }} --> A '''Blue Mass''' is a [[Mass (liturgy)|Mass]] celebrated annually in the [[Catholic Church]] for those employed in the "public safety field" (i.e. [[police officer]]s, [[firefighter]]s, [[correctional officer]]s, [[911 operator]]s and [[Emergency medical services|EMS personnel]]).<ref name="oakland">{{cite web |url=https://oaklandnorth.net/2014/10/14/oakland-police-firefighters-honored-at-oakland-blue-mass |title=Oakland police, firefighters honored at Blue Mass |publisher=Oakland North |date=2014-10-14 |website= |accessdate=26 December 2014}}</ref> The color blue relates to the blue-colored uniforms predominantly used by these services.<ref name="Walla Walla Union-Bulletin - 30 September 2014 - St. Pat's hosts Blue Mass for law enforcers">{{cite news|url=http://union-bulletin.com/news/2014/sep/30/st-pats-hosts-blue-mass-law-enforcers|archive-url=https://archive.is/20141226052629/http://union-bulletin.com/news/2014/sep/30/st-pats-hosts-blue-mass-law-enforcers|dead-url=yes|archive-date=26 December 2014|title=St. Pat's hosts Blue Mass for law enforcers|last=Charnley Eveland|first=Annie|work=[[Walla Walla Union-Bulletin]]|publisher=[[The Seattle Times Company]]|date=30 September 2014|website=|accessdate=26 December 2014}}</ref> Similar to the Red Mass, the service honors those who have died in the line of duty and those currently serving as first responders.<ref name="cardinal">{{cite web |url=http://cardinalsblog.adw.org/2014/05/with-prayers-and-gratitude-the-blue-mass |title= With Prayers and Gratitude: The Blue Mass |last= [[Donald Wuerl|Wuerl]] |first=Donald |publisher=[[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Washington|Archdiocese of Washington]] |date=2014-05-14 |website= Cardinal's Blog |accessdate=26 December 2014}}</ref> The Mass is an opportunity for the community to show gratitude to first responders and their families.<ref name="angels">{{cite web |url=http://angelsoveramerica.org/press-release/what-is-a-blue-mass |title=What is a Blue Mass? |last= Long |first=Carolyn K. |publisher=Angels Over America |date=2011-08-05 |website= |accessdate=26 December 2014}}</ref>
==Background== In Washington, D.C. the service is held in conjunction with [[National Police Week]].<ref name="angels" /> Psalm 91:11, "For He will give His angels [especial] charge over you to accompany and defend and preserve you in all your ways [of obedience and service]," are often invoked during the service.<ref name="angels" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.saintpatrickdc.org/bluemass.shtml |title=20th Annual Blue Mass |publisher=St. Patrick Catholic Church|date=2014-05-06 |website= |accessdate=26 December 2014}}</ref> Though usually held in a Catholic church, the events are generally considered to be [[ecumenical]] or non-denominational.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.desertsun.com/story/news/local/2014/09/23/blue-mass-indio-riverside-county/16087179/ |title= Showing gratitude for those who serve | publisher=Saint David of Wales Catholic parish |date=2014-09-22|website= |accessdate=26 December 2014}}</ref>
The Blue Mass dates to September 29, 1934,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://colton.citynewsgroup.com/articles/dee231827be1f6f54562bc50d8ed2cba |title=Blue Mass Honors Fallen Police and Firefighters |publisher=City News Group Inc. |date=2014-10-24 |website= Colton City News |accessdate=26 December 2014}}</ref> when Rev. Thomas Dade started the service as part of his duties with the Catholic Police and Fireman’s Society.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1994-11-17/news/1994321074_1_roman-catholic-church-priest-pastor-of-st |title=Msgr. Thomas B. Dade, was pastor in Riverdale |publisher=Baltimore Sun |date=1994-11-17 |website= |accessdate=26 December 2014}}</ref> The first mass was held at [[St. Patrick's Catholic Church (Washington, D.C.)|St. Patrick’s Catholic Church]] in Washington, D.C. and has grown to a nationwide celebration.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.stdavidofwales.com/pr---blue-mass.html |title=LOCAL PARISH HAS "BLUE MASS" TO HONOR AND PRAY FOR FIRST RESPONDERS: POLICE, FIRE AND MEDICAL | publisher=Saint David of Wales Catholic parish |date=2014-09-01 |website= |accessdate=26 December 2014}}</ref> The September 29 service was timed to coincide with [[Michaelmas#Modern observances|Michaelmas]], the feast of [[Michael (archangel)|Saint Michael the Archangel]], the [[patron saint|patron]] [[military saint]] of police officers and [[military]].
