[[Category:Socialism]]

'''The Study of Administration''' is an 1887 article by [[Woodrow Wilson]] in [[Political Science Quarterly]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Wilson |first1=Woodrow |year=1887 |title=The Study of Administration |journal=Political Science Quarterly |volume=2 |issue=2 |pages=197–222 |url=http://teachingamericanhistory.org/library/index.asp?document=465 |accessdate=9 December 2012}}</ref>  It is widely considered a foundational article in the field of [[public administration]], making Wilson one of the field's founding fathers, along with [[Max Weber]] and [[Frederick Winslow Taylor]].<ref name="Hood2000">{{cite book|author=Christopher Hood|title=The Art of the State: Culture, Rhetoric, and Public Management|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ns7wTyXuw5sC|accessdate=15 December 2012|date=30 March 2000|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-829765-9|page=76}}</ref>

Although colleges were already teaching [[Public administration|administration]] in the 1880s, it was considered a sub-field of [[political science]].  Wilson argued that it should be treated as its own field of study, with public administrators being directly responsible to political leaders.  He believed that politicians should be accountable to the people and that political administration should be treated as a science, and its practitioners given authority to address issues in their respective fields.<ref>{{cite web | title = Woodrow Wilson on Administration | url = http://www.heritage.org/initiatives/first-principles/primary-sources/woodrow-wilson-on-administration | accessdate = 2012-12-15}}</ref>

